# Descriptive Analysis

## Tabular analysis
characteristics of the `r nrow(CDC_tobacco)` viruses from the CDC_PRAMStat database are displayed in the table below.
```{r make-analytic}
analytic <- CDC_tobacco %>%
  filter(QuestionId %in% c("QUO30", "QUO31")) %>%
  mutate(
    TimePeriod = case_when(
      QuestionId == "QUO30" ~ "3 months before pregnancy",
      QuestionId == "QUO31" ~ "Last 3 months of pregnancy"
    )
  )
```

```{r, table}
library(tidyverse)
library(gt)

clean_table <- analytic %>%
  select(LocationDesc, TimePeriod, Data_Value) %>%
  pivot_wider(
    names_from = TimePeriod,
    values_from = Data_Value
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    Reduction = `3 months before pregnancy` - `Last 3 months of pregnancy`
  ) %>%
  rename(
    Location = LocationDesc,
    Before = `3 months before pregnancy`,
    During = `Last 3 months of pregnancy`
  ) %>%
  arrange(desc(Reduction))

clean_table %>%
  gt() %>%
  tab_header(
    title = "Smoking Prevalence Before vs Late Pregnancy (2011)",
    subtitle = "CDC PRAMStat"
  ) %>%
  cols_label(
    Before = "Before Pregnancy (%)",
    During = "Last 3 Months (%)",
    Reduction = "Absolute Reduction (%)"
  ) %>%
  fmt_number(columns = c(Before, During, Reduction), decimals = 1)
  


```
Table 1 summarizes smoking prevalence before pregnancy and during the last trimester across participating locations in 2011. All locations show a reduction in smoking prevalence during pregnancy. The largest absolute reductions were observed in New Mexico (16.9%) and Nebraska (16.3 %), whereas smaller reductions were observed in Utah and New York City.


## Graphical analysis
Below I present a bar graph comparing smoking prevalence before pregnancy and during the last trimester across locations in the United States.

```{r figure, fig.width=8, fig.height=5}
plot_df <- analytic %>%
  group_by(LocationDesc, TimePeriod) %>%
  summarise(Prevalence = mean(Data_Value, na.rm = TRUE),
            .groups = "drop")

ggplot(plot_df, aes(x = LocationDesc, y = Prevalence, fill = TimePeriod)) +
  geom_col(position = "dodge") +
  labs(
    title = "Maternal Smoking Before vs Late Pregnancy by Location",
    x = "Location",
    y = "Smoking Prevalence (%)",
    fill = "Time Period"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1),
    text = element_text(size = 12)
  )

```

Figure 1 compares smoking prevalence before pregnancy and during the last trimester across locations in 2011. Smoking prevalence was lowest in New York City and highest in West Virginia across both time periods, highlighting substantial geographic variation in maternal smoking patterns.




